<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-757-582  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 757 582.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Industrial Engineering  August 1990 v22 n8 p23(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Productivity implementation management must start with commitmentfrom the top. (health care industry)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Whitman, Alan R.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Health organization managers must understand what productivity isand how it can be measured before making successful changes.andO;Guidelines for the eight-step Productivity ManagementImplementation Process are provided.andP;  These eight processes aregiven the acronym CEOWIMPS.andP;  The 'C' stands for credible system;any information presented must be backed with data.andP;  Standardsestablished for measuring productivity must be fair ('E').andP;  Thesize of the organization ('O') needs to be taken intoconsideration and the workers ('W') need to understand whatproductivity is and be involved in planning for it.andP;  Incentives('I') are important to implementing the monitoring program and alllevels of management ('M') must be committed to carrying it out.andO;Without a positive attitude ('P') commitment is simply notpossible.andP;  The process of change takes time, and staying power('S') will determine the success of the implementations.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Health CareGuidelinesProductivityManagementExecutive.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>